what is interblockchain

Subtensor is a substrate chain which is a blockchain built with Polkadot's custom API for building chains which are interoperable with others within the Polkadot ecosystem. Parachains are substrate chains which have bonded their consensus mechanism with the Polkadot main chain which enables transactions to be be doubled across your local chain and the the main "relay chain". Parathreads, are pay as you go Parachains. There is a protocol written by polkadot which I am calling their Interblockchain protocol, which enables two substrate chains to double transactions across both chains simultaneously. This functionality is what enables Parachains, but it can be used between any two substrate chains to to atomic swaps and other functionality. We could for instance, outsource governance to a secondary chain and only do votes etc from that chain.
so you could create something like uniswap for these parachains
Everything on Ethereum will be built with substrate chains IMO
the difference is that you need to trust the consensus of the two chains. A swap is only as secure as the weakest of the chains.

Welcome welcome!

So, there's no way to know what nodes are running which model. Instead, each Bittensor model identifies which model is most useful to it through it's PKM layer (think mixture of experts, but on an internet scale). Through that, it's able to understand which model communicates in which modality (Text, Image, Video, etc.). And then it will only match up and communicate with other nodes that have the same modality
This way, NLP models will talk to NLP models, for example, and ignore image models, etc.

The peer finding is covered in the white paper, but to sum it up we essentially use a modified version of the page rank algorithm (called peer rank) where a node can identify which peer is most useful to it by measuring the change to its loss function if that peer were no longer on the network.
@lum it's absolutely encouraged if you can propose a new model architecture!
we are still alpha 2.0 🙂 so we'd love research/development/ideas to improve the network and all that
additionally, right now we only support text modality, we are working on covering image, audio, etc.
I'm not sure if we got into polkadot yet 🙂 i think we're just shortlisted no?
also, if you need any help/rundown please feel free to ping myself or the other devs!

Neat! Yeah i guess fetch ai is tackling a similar problem. The difference with Bittensor is that models are able to figure out for themselves who is most useful to them using the ranking mechanism.. If you rank highly, other nodes will automatically start gravitating towards your node since its rank is higher than others
so from a game-theoretic approach, it's sort of self-democratizing, as opposed to creating a democratization mechanism like fetch did

At first look I wondered how bittensor can get independent ML miners to exchange intelligence, because there could be many different objective functions to optimize. How does bittensor get ML miners to agree on one objective? This is important because it determines which datasets to train on, how training should be supervised, and how the model should be architected.
Then I saw bittensor basically chose the most universal unsupervised objective that is actually useful: "Predict the next/missing word" (for text).

So this is excellent, since the ability to predict the next word can harnessed to do all sorts of NLG (natural language generation) and NLI (inference). Apart from exchanging intelligence, I see the value of bittensor as a compute engine that can be queried by users for NLG/NLI functionality.

The tremendous uptake of the GPT3 API for NLG purposes is a prime example of this value. However, since workloads submitted to bittensor are essentially plaintext, it brings into question security/IP concerns, and market competition bringing commercial APIs to the same pricepoint where the affordability, privacy, and speed of an Azure/AWS/GC GPT3-like API will then be greatly preferred.
That is why I think bittensor needs to work toward further differentiation, which I think could be finetuning objectives for large-scale LMs based on more domain-specific text datasets.

Alternatively, to address the concern of over-replication of models in bittensor, and a question about the efficacy of co-distillation, lum's Kademlia direction of parameter/model parallelism could be considered. Since compute memory is a primary limitation in ML, 3D parallelism (model/parameter/data) makes a lot of sense for a distributed compute network.

However, I do think that bittensor's core functionality of message-passing and node-definable utility rewarding is a solid generic basis, upon which aforementioned ideas can be implemented without having to change the core. So bittensor, to me at least, appears very extensible and can support many different directions.

That's a good point. We're actually trying to figure out the best way to obfuscate this information, but at this point in time the project is too nascent to compete with azure/aws/etc anyways, so most companies will likely choose them right now because they're much more mature. As the network grows, data security will become more important to address, for sure.

And we don't need to limit ourselves towards predicting the next word in the sentence, this is just most common language modeling technique. Anything that builds a representation of language will be useful to the collective.

I agree that Bittensor needs to work towards greater diversification in the models used, the training algorithms, even different subsets of language, however, there is no need to separate the network. The purpose of all modern state of the art language models, BER, GPT, XLM, transformerXL, etc is to produce a representation which is commonly useful to all domain specific problems i.e a form of general intelligence. The purpose of Bittensor is to find that here, at the intersection of all these various approaches, but under a common standard tensor encoding and in a common network.
I imagine it could be very successful for users to train hyper domain specific models into Bittensor i.e. a language model which only understood Pinterest or only a specific Twitter hash tags

messages.content: Ok. Thanks.  I`ll view it. Final question:  What would be an example of ML information that would be sent (i.e. that is being generated by the process I`m running). If that requires a super-elaborate answer, ignore the question.

It's a little complicated, but i'll do my best to make a short and simplified answer 🙂 

Basically, a regular ML model takes a batch of the dataset, trains on it, then checks if its training is correct by checking its loss function (loss closer to 0 the better). The model then uses something called a backpropagation algorithm to get the gradients (amount by which to update its parameters) and starts training again on another batch. These "gradients" are the information being passed around that I mentioned. 

With Bittensor, the model shares its batch of dataset with its nPeers, each peer will train on this batch, then return their outputs back to your bittensor model. Your bittensor model will use that output as input to itself, (see how we are stitching neural networks together?) and then it will produce gradients as well. This gradient is send back to the peers. Everyone updates themselves accordingly.
This is outlined in much better detail in our paper here: https://arxiv.org/abs/2003.03917
